# CONSULT-29-B: Tri-STRIP skeletal read-past trace

## Verdict

| Question | Answer |
|----------|--------|
| **Is the tri-STRIP read-past hazard real in code?** | **YES** — strip indices are uncompacted; tri-list indices are compacted. |
| **Is it LIVE for Jawa / dewback / robe spikes today?** | **NO** — no skeletal asset populates strips; `drawPartialIndexedTriangleStrip` never fires. |

The CONSULT-24 read-past mechanism is **implemented but dormant** on all shipped skeletal IFF assets. The live spike is **not** explained by this path (handoff §4 agrees: tri-LIST `readPast=0`, no strip draws).

---

## 1. Do skeletal meshes actually use triangle strips?

**No — not in practice.** The strip *render* path exists, but nothing in the skeletal mesh pipeline feeds it.

**IFF loader only accepts tri-lists.** `SkeletalMeshGeneratorTemplate` defines `TAG_ITL` / `TAG_OITL` only; the primitive switch handles those two cases and fatals on anything else:

```1466:1488:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/SkeletalMeshGeneratorTemplate.cpp
					case TAG_ITL:
						{
							IndexedTriListPrimitive *const drawPrimitive = new IndexedTriListPrimitive();
							drawPrimitive->load_0002(iff, positions, m_positionIndices, zeroAreaTriCount);

							m_drawPrimitives.push_back(drawPrimitive);
						}
						break;
					case TAG_OITL:
						{
							OccludedIndexedTriListPrimitive *const drawPrimitive = new OccludedIndexedTriListPrimitive();
							drawPrimitive->load_0002(iff, positions, m_positionIndices, zeroAreaTriCount);

							m_drawPrimitives.push_back(drawPrimitive);
						}
						break;
					default:
						{
							char buffer[5];

							ConvertTagToString(iff.getCurrentName(), buffer);
							FATAL(true, ("unsupported draw primitive [%s]", buffer));
						}
```

**Strip population APIs have zero call sites** anywhere under `src/`:

- `MeshConstructionHelper::addTriStrip` — defined at `MeshConstructionHelper.cpp:1036`
- `MeshConstructionHelper::addTriStripVertex` — defined at `MeshConstructionHelper.cpp:1060`
- Grep across all of `src/` finds **only** those definitions + headers; no callers.

**`buildIndexBufferAndRenderCommands` branch selection** (`SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1469–1577`):

| Condition | Emits |
|-----------|-------|
| `triListCount = mesh.getTriListCount(...)` > 0 | `RenderCommand::createTriList` → `Graphics::drawIndexedTriangleList` (`:267–275`, `:1537`) |
| `triStripCount = mesh.getTriStripCount(...)` > 0 | `RenderCommand::createTriStrip` → `Graphics::drawIndexedTriangleStrip` (`:280–289`, `:1575`) |

For all standard skeletal assets (Jawa, dewback, robes, every LOD loaded via `SkeletalMeshGeneratorTemplate`), `triStripCount == 0` always → only `createTriList` is emitted.

**Runtime confirmation:** instrumented `drawPartialIndexedTriangleStrip` writes `cape-strip-probe.txt`; handoff reports **no output** → zero strip draws during Jawa/dewback spike sessions (`2026-06-07-cape-spike-softskin-ring-discard-renderdoc-next.md` §5).

---

## 2. Can raw tri-strip indices exceed `m_vertexCount - 1`?

**YES — by construction, if strips were ever populated.**

### Index compaction (tri-LIST — correct)

`prepareForReading()` assigns compacted `m_shaderVertexIndex` ∈ `[0, m_usedVertexCount)` only to referenced vertices (`MeshConstructionHelper.cpp:543–567`).

`getTriListTriangle()` remaps at IB-build time through that compacted index:

```1479:1489:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/MeshConstructionHelper.cpp
	//-- return fixed-up indices (tri indices were submitted assuming nothing was dropped out)
	NOT_NULL(perShaderData);

	const size_t  vertexDataIndex0 = perShaderData->m_vertexIndices[static_cast<size_t>((*m_indexedTriangles)[indexedTriangleIndex * 3 + 0])];
	index0                         = m_vertexData->m_container[vertexDataIndex0].m_shaderVertexIndex;

	const size_t  vertexDataIndex1 = perShaderData->m_vertexIndices[static_cast<size_t>((*m_indexedTriangles)[indexedTriangleIndex * 3 + 1])];
	index1                         = m_vertexData->m_container[vertexDataIndex1].m_shaderVertexIndex;

	const size_t  vertexDataIndex2 = perShaderData->m_vertexIndices[static_cast<size_t>((*m_indexedTriangles)[indexedTriangleIndex * 3 + 2])];
	index2                         = m_vertexData->m_container[vertexDataIndex2].m_shaderVertexIndex;
```

### Strip path (uncompacted — hazard)

`addTriStripVertex()` stores the **loose** slot index (into `perShaderData->m_vertexIndices`) directly, with no compaction:

```1083:1085:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/MeshConstructionHelper.cpp
	// add shader vertex index to strip
	m_triStripIndices->m_container.push_back(static_cast<size_t>(shaderVertexIndex));
	++triStripHeader.m_indexCount;
```

Validation permits any loose slot `< m_vertexIndices.size()` (`:1068`), **not** `< m_usedVertexCount`.

`getTriStripVertexIndex()` returns that raw stored value — **no** `m_shaderVertexIndex` remap:

```1426:1434:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/MeshConstructionHelper.cpp
int MeshConstructionHelper::getTriStripVertexIndex(const TriStripHeader &triStripHeader, int vertexIndex) const
{
	NOT_NULL(m_triStripIndices);
	VALIDATE_RANGE_INCLUSIVE_EXCLUSIVE(0, vertexIndex, triStripHeader.m_indexCount);

	const size_t indexIntoTriStripIndex = static_cast<size_t>(triStripHeader.m_firstTriStripIndex + vertexIndex);
	VALIDATE_RANGE_INCLUSIVE_EXCLUSIVE(0U, indexIntoTriStripIndex, m_triStripIndices->m_container.size() ); //lint !e1703

	return static_cast<int>(m_triStripIndices->m_container[indexIntoTriStripIndex]);
}
```

Those raw values are copied straight into the IB (`SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1565–1566`).

### vs `m_vertexCount`

```1187:1188:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp
	m_vertexCount = mesh.getVertexCount(meshPerShaderData);
	DEBUG_FATAL(m_vertexCount < 1, ("there are no vertices!"));
```

```1234:1237:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/MeshConstructionHelper.cpp
int MeshConstructionHelper::getVertexCount(const PerShaderData *perShaderData) const
{
	NOT_NULL(perShaderData);
	return perShaderData->m_usedVertexCount;
}
```

Render path writes exactly that many vertices:

```754:758:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp
			m_dynamicStream->lock(m_vertexCount);
			{
				VertexBufferWriteIterator writeIterator = m_dynamicStream->begin();
				skinData(transformCount, transformArray, writeIterator);
			}
```

**Mismatch:** loose strip indices can be as large as `m_vertexIndices.size() - 1` (full per-shader slot table, including culled unused vertices), while only `m_usedVertexCount` vertices are written. Any loose index `>= m_usedVertexCount` would fetch past the locked slice.

The in-tree `CAPE-INDEX-PROBE` at `SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1589–1633` checks `maxIdx >= capeVertexCount` (= `m_usedVertexCount`) across the combined IB; on tri-list-only assets this stays `overRead=0`.

---

## 3. D3D9 vs D3D11 strip draw with over-range index

### Dispatch chain

```
RenderCommand::render()                    SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:314
  → Graphics::drawIndexedTriangleStrip()   Graphics.cpp:3340–3344
    → D3D9: drawIndexedTriangleStrip()    Direct3d9.cpp:4517–4526
    → D3D11: drawPartialIndexedTriangleStrip()  Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:3457–3549
```

### D3D9 (`Direct3d9.cpp:4517–4526`, `:4157`)

```4517:4526:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9.cpp
void Direct3d9Namespace::drawIndexedTriangleStrip(int baseIndex, int minimumVertexIndex, int numberOfVertices, int startIndex, int primitiveCount)
{
#ifdef _DEBUG
	if (!shouldDraw(true, primitiveCount))
		return;

	Direct3d9_Metrics::triangles += primitiveCount;
	Direct3d9_Metrics::perPassTriangles[ms_currentPassIndex] += primitiveCount;
#endif
	Direct3d9::drawIndexedPrimitive(D3DPT_TRIANGLESTRIP, baseIndex, minimumVertexIndex, numberOfVertices, startIndex, primitiveCount, primitiveCount + 2);
}
```

`DrawIndexedPrimitive` receives **`MinVertexIndex`** and **`NumVertices`** (`minimumVertexIndex`, `numberOfVertices` from the render command = `minVbIndex` and `(maxVbIndex - minVbIndex) + 1`). D3D9 uses these to declare the vertex span the draw may reference. Neither API **clamps** out-of-range indices — behavior is undefined — but D3D9's declared span can still be very large if uncompacted strip maxima are large.

On the shared dynamic ring, D3D9's tail often holds **stale non-zero geometry** from prior writes (CONSULT-24), so read-past may look like mild garbage rather than a clean collapse to origin.

### D3D11 (`Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:3457–3549`)

```3546:3549:D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp
	Direct3d11_Device::getContext()->DrawIndexed(
		static_cast<UINT>(primitiveCount + 2),
		static_cast<UINT>(startIndex),
		static_cast<INT>(baseIndex));
```

**`minimumVertexIndex` and `numberOfVertices` are ignored** for the actual draw (only used inside the diagnostic probe). D3D11 `DrawIndexed` has no vertex-range bound. An index `>= m_vertexCount` fetches from the ring slice past the `lock(m_vertexCount)` write; staging probes show that tail is **zeroed** on WRITE_DISCARD generations → vertices collapse to `(0,0,0)` → origin fan / spike.

### `cape-strip-probe` (lines 3462–3543)

Built to mirror the tri-LIST staging probe for the **strip** path. On each sampled soft-skin strip draw (`stride==48`, `8 <= numberOfVertices <= 4000`):

1. `CopySubresourceRegion` first 256 verts from the bound VB at draw offset
2. Scans positions for longest run of identical `(x,y,z)` (threshold `1e-8`)
3. Computes `ssMaxIndex = minimumVertexIndex + numberOfVertices - 1`
4. Sets `readPast=1` when `longestRun >= 16` **and** `ssMaxIndex >= runStart` (collapse run extends into the declared vertex span)
5. Logs to `cape-strip-probe.txt`: `COLLAPSE`/`HB`, call#, bound offset, minVtx, numVtx, maxIndex, runStart, readPast, longestRun, firstPos

**Result:** no file produced → **no strip draws hit this path** during spike reproduction.

---

## 4. Is a degenerate strip a natural "radiating shard" producer?

**Yes.** Triangle-strip topology fans each new vertex with the previous two strip vertices. If one strip index resolves to a collapsed/garbage position (e.g. ring zero-tail at origin) while neighbors are valid world-local positions, every subsequent strip triangle shares that bad vertex as one corner → thin triangles radiating from a point. That matches the observed "most verts collapse, a few stay correct, triangles fan out" look. Tri-LIST degeneracy tends to produce isolated bad triangles; **strip amplifies one bad vertex across many consecutive triangles**, which is why strip read-past is a particularly sharp spike mechanism.

---

## Summary table

| Stage | Tri-LIST (live) | Tri-STRIP (dormant) |
|-------|-----------------|---------------------|
| IFF tags | `TAG_ITL`, `TAG_OITL` | None |
| IB index source | `getTriListTriangle` → compacted `m_shaderVertexIndex` | `getTriStripVertexIndex` → raw loose slot |
| Max index vs `m_vertexCount` | `≤ m_usedVertexCount - 1` | Can be `≥ m_usedVertexCount` |
| Draw function | `drawPartialIndexedTriangleList` | `drawPartialIndexedTriangleStrip` |
| D3D11 vertex bound | None (but indices in-range) | None + indices can be out-of-range |
| Observed at runtime | Instrumented, `readPast=0` | Never called |

---

## Bottom line for CONSULT-24

- **Code-level hazard:** YES — the strip IB path would read past the `lock(m_vertexCount)` slice in D3D11 because `getTriStripVertexIndex` (`MeshConstructionHelper.cpp:1434`) returns uncompacted loose indices while `m_vertexCount` (`SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1187`) is the compacted `m_usedVertexCount`.
- **Live on Jawa / dewback / robes:** NO — `addTriStripVertex` has no callers; `triStripCount` is always 0; `cape-strip-probe.txt` is empty. These creatures spike via the **tri-LIST** soft-skin dynamic-ring path, which is index-clean. The spike cause remains the ring-discard invalidation hypothesis (handoff §3), not tri-STRIP read-past.
